# Key Learning
Each level demonstrated a distinct class of weak password practice that is common in real environments. Default credentials (Level 1) remain one of the most exploited attack vectors in IT and OT environments. Company keyword passwords (Level 2) are predictable when keywords are publicly visible on the organisation's own website. Personal information passwords (Level 3) can be systematically generated using tools like CUPP when basic OSINT is available. Hashing filenames with SHA256 does not protect against dictionary cracking if the original values are common words. Self-disclosed password patterns (Level 5) on social profiles give attackers a precise recipe for generating targeted wordlists, eliminating the need for exhaustive brute force.

# What I Would Flag in a Real SOC
- Default credentials on any management interface (admin/12345) should be flagged as critical and remediated before the system is exposed to any network segment
- Passwords derived from publicly visible website keywords are trivially guessable, any organisation using company terminology in password policies should be advised to enforce complexity requirements and MFA
- CUPP-style attacks are highly effective when employee personal information is accessible via internal portals or public profiles, access to employee directories should be scoped and authenticated
- Hashing filenames using SHA256 of the original name provides no security if the original values are common dictionary words, a random UUID or salt should be used instead
- A user publicly sharing their password construction pattern on a company social platform is a critical security awareness failure and should be addressed through staff training
- SSH exposed on a standard port without rate limiting or MFA allows unlimited brute force attempts, fail2ban or equivalent and key-based authentication should be enforced as a baseline
- Claude AI was used effectively in this room to generate Hydra commands and wordlist scripts, demonstrating that AI tools significantly lower the technical barrier for password auditing, defenders must account for AI-assisted attacks in their threat models
